properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls continuing through today. Local snowfall accumulations of 10 to 20 cm will be possible by tonight under the most intense snow squalls. Gusty winds will accompany these snow squalls at times resulting in periods of blowing snow. These snow squalls are expected to slowly shift southward as the wind becomes northwesterly by this evening. Additional snowfall accumulations of 15 cm are possible tonight. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls may develop this afternoon or this evening. Flurries will continue today due to gusty westerly winds. Snow squalls with reduced visibility may develop or intensify later today and continue in a few locations into Thursday morning. Local snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are possible. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A Pacific weather system will bring snow along sections of the Coquihalla Highway from Hope to Merritt. Snow will increase in intensity overnight and continue into Thursday morning as the system passes through the region. The heavy snow will ease in intensity through Thursday but periods of snow is still expected. Snow levels will remain near valley bottom except near Hope where rain is expected. Total snow amounts up to 25 cm may fall during the event for tonight and Thursday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills continues. A cold arctic airmass is expected to remain in place throughout the week. Wind chills will moderate daily, before falling into the minus 40 to 50 range during the overnight to morning periods. Increasing cloud this evening for the Fort McMurray region should keep the region from experiencing -40 wind chills tonight. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible tonight. Winds are expected to shift to westerly over Lake Superior this afternoon leading to the redevelopment of snow squalls early this evening. Local snowfall accumulations of 10 cm will be possible under the most intense snow squalls tonight. A general snowfall will follow on Thursday with another 5 cm of accumulation possible. Gusty winds will accompany these snow squalls at times resulting in periods of blowing snow. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls continue today. Local snowfall amounts up to 15 cm will be possible. Gusty winds will accompany these snow squalls at times, resulting in periods of blowing snow. The snow squalls will shift northward out of the Sault St. Marie area this evening but will continue for areas near and south of Montreal River. An additional 15 cm of accumulation will be possible locally tonight for those areas. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Long-lasting blizzard conditions with potentially damaging winds and persistent visibility near zero in blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong ridge of high pressure is in place over the Northwest Territories. With low pressure over Alaska, strong winds with blowing snow are expected for northern sections of the Dempster. Near the Richardson Mountains, winds will reach 90 km/h gusting to 120 at times resulting in blizzard conditions. Blizzard conditions are forecast to improve by late Thursday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A frontal system passing over Haida Gwaii this morning will cause winds to increase from southeasterly 60 km/h gusting 80 to southeasterly 90 km/h gusting 110. As the system moves eastward, winds will ease early this evening. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Additional snowfall: 5 to 10 cm today and tonight. Maximum wind gusts: 80 to 110 km/h. Locations: Nain to Makkovik Time span: continuing until midnight tonight. Remarks: Fresh snowfall has combined with strengthening westerly winds this morning to produce poor visibility in blowing snow in Nain. Snow and blowing snow will spread southward to Hopedale and Postville-Makkovik this afternoon. Conditions are expected to improve tonight as the snow tapers off. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
